../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/ckn-1982-proof-architecture.md:65:### Precise Statement (CKN 1982, Proposition 2 / Theorem B)
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/ckn-1982-proof-architecture.md:67:**CKN ε-Regularity Theorem:** There exists an absolute constant ε₀ > 0 (depending only on dimension n = 3, with no other parameters) such that:
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/ckn-1982-proof-architecture.md:73:**What "regular" means precisely (CKN §2):** z₀ is regular if there exists ρ > 0 such that u ∈ L^∞(Q_ρ(z₀)). Equivalently, u ∈ C^{0,α}(Q_ρ(z₀)) for some α > 0 (CKN prove that L^∞ and Hölder continuity are equivalent at the level of NS — this is the core of their Bootstrap lemma, their Lemma 2.3).
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/ckn-1982-proof-architecture.md:81:CKN also prove (their Theorem A, Proposition 1) that either of the following alone implies regularity at z₀:
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/ckn-1982-proof-architecture.md:91:**Condition (III) — Pressure-free version (Lin 1998 simplified this):** CKN show the combined condition A+E+C+D is sufficient; Lin (1998) showed that under mild conditions A(r) ≤ ε₀ alone suffices (his Theorem 1.1).
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/ckn-1982-proof-architecture.md:98:- **E(r)** — time-integrated H¹ semi-norm; the local dissipation. Appears from the local energy inequality (LEI) directly.
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/ckn-1982-proof-architecture.md:108:### The Vitali Covering Construction (CKN §3)
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/ckn-1982-proof-architecture.md:110:The covering argument occupies §3 of CKN. The key steps are:
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/ckn-1982-proof-architecture.md:150:**The dimension in Euclidean terms:** The parabolic 1-dimensional Hausdorff measure P¹ = 0 (which is what CKN prove, i.e., P¹(Σ) = 0, not just finite) corresponds in Euclidean space-time ℝ^{3+1} to Hausdorff dimension ≤ 5/3 ≈ 1.667. The reason: a set of parabolic dimension d has Euclidean space-time dimension d + (d/2)·(1/1) ... actually: if a set S ⊆ ℝ³×ℝ has parabolic Hausdorff dimension d_P, its Euclidean Hausdorff dimension d_E satisfies d_P ≤ d_E × (5/4) in general, with exact conversion depending on geometry. The standard statement is: P¹(Σ) = 0 implies that the 1-dimensional Lebesgue measure of the projection of Σ onto the time axis is zero (this is how Scheffer, 1976, originally stated the result; CKN improve to P¹ = 0 which is stronger).
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/ckn-1982-proof-architecture.md:152:**CKN's actual statement (Theorem C):** "The singular set Σ has one-dimensional (parabolic) Hausdorff measure zero." Explicitly: P¹(Σ) = 0. This implies in particular that Σ cannot contain any curve (not even a Lipschitz arc) in ℝ⁴.
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/ckn-1982-proof-architecture.md:176:CKN's localization uses smooth cutoff functions in space-time. Let φ = φ(x,t) be a standard cutoff:
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/ckn-1982-proof-architecture.md:181:The local energy inequality (LEI) integrated against φ gives (from CKN §2):
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/ckn-1982-proof-architecture.md:213:To get local L^{3/2} control of p from local L³ control of u, CKN use a decomposition:
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/ckn-1982-proof-architecture.md:241:By the CKN pressure decomposition technique (see CKN §3, and Robinson-Rodrigo-Sadowski Ch.13 §13.3), p_2 is controlled by the non-local part of the pressure, which in turn is bounded by global L^{3/2} norms of u far from x₀.
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/ckn-1982-proof-architecture.md:249:### The Bootstrap (CKN Proposition 3 / Lemma 2.3)
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/ckn-1982-proof-architecture.md:251:After establishing the local energy estimate, CKN run the following bootstrap:
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/ckn-1982-proof-architecture.md:258:1. u ∈ L²_t H¹_x (global) + local energy inequality → E(r) controlled
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/ckn-1982-proof-architecture.md:269:The key embedding (CKN §3, using the parabolic Sobolev inequality):
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/ckn-1982-proof-architecture.md:349:CKN's proof uses Young's inequality in several places. I identify the main ones with the powers used.
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/ckn-1982-proof-architecture.md:367:**Young Step Y2: Vortex stretching term in enstrophy estimate (appears in intermediate bootstrap)**
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/ckn-1982-proof-architecture.md:389:The Gagliardo-Nirenberg interpolation used in CKN (parabolic version):
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/ckn-1982-proof-architecture.md:397:**Young Step Y4: The absorption step in the CKN "pressure-regularity" lemma**
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/ckn-1982-proof-architecture.md:413:| Y1 | Pressure term in local energy inequality | 3/2 and 3 | No (ε = 1) | Separate pressure and velocity |
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/ckn-1982-proof-architecture.md:418:The key observation: **Y2 is the most significant lossy step.** The Ladyzhenskaya inequality with free parameter δ is where the proof is intentionally lossy — the power 3/2 of ||∇u||_{L²} in the vortex-stretching-type term forces a Young's inequality that introduces ν⁻³ or equivalent factors. In the *local* setting of CKN, the dissipation is sufficient to close (because the local energy inequality gives a uniform estimate), but the lossiness here is what prevents explicit computation of ε₀.
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/ckn-1982-proof-architecture.md:424:The complete proof architecture of CKN (1982):
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/ckn-1982-proof-architecture.md:427:1. Define suitable weak solutions (u,p) satisfying NS + local energy inequality (LEI)
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/ckn-1982-proof-architecture.md:469:The proof architecture makes clear where the dimension bound 1 comes from, and why it cannot be improved within the CKN framework:
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/ckn-1982-proof-architecture.md:477:which would require E(r, z₀) ≥ ε₀ · r^{s-1} → ∞ as r → 0 for singular points. This cannot be guaranteed by the structure of the local energy inequality alone — it would require knowing that the dissipation concentrates even more strongly at singular points. Whether Type I singular points (where |u(x,t)| ≤ C/√(T*-t)) satisfy such enhanced concentration is a deep open question.
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/ckn-1982-proof-architecture.md:479:**What CKN leaves open:** The gap between "P¹(Σ) = 0" and "Σ = ∅" (full regularity). Filling this gap requires either:
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/ckn-1982-proof-architecture.md:481:(b) Additional geometric/analytic information about NS singular points beyond what the local energy inequality provides.
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/ckn-1982-proof-architecture.md:487:For the comparison with Lin (1998) and Vasseur (2007), the key signatures of CKN are:
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/ckn-1982-proof-architecture.md:489:| Feature | CKN (1982) signature |
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/ckn-1982-proof-architecture.md:501:The direct/explicit style means CKN's proof is quantitative in structure but non-quantitative in constants. Every estimate is of the form "LHS ≤ C × RHS" with explicit powers of r, but C is determined by chains of Sobolev/CZ constants that are not computed.
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/ckn-1982-proof-architecture.md:507:**On the local energy inequality:** CKN Definition 2.2 and the discussion in §2. This inequality was first used by Scheffer (1976); CKN strengthened the partial regularity result by proving P¹(Σ) = 0 (Scheffer had only proven the time-Lebesgue measure of the singular set is zero).
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/ckn-1982-proof-architecture.md:509:**On the scale-invariant quantities A, E, C, D:** CKN §2. The specific normalization (1/r and 1/r²) is chosen to make each quantity dimensionless under NS scaling.
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/ckn-1982-proof-architecture.md:511:**On Condition (I) vs. the full criterion:** CKN prove in Proposition 1 that Condition (I) alone (only E(r) < ε₀) is sufficient if one additionally assumes the solution is in L^{10/3} near z₀. Their Proposition 2 handles the full local case with all four quantities.
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/ckn-1982-proof-architecture.md:513:**On the parabolic Hausdorff measure:** CKN §3 and Theorem C. The definition P^s(Σ) uses parabolic cylinders Q_r with "radius" r counted in the parabolic metric (so Q_r has parabolic "diameter" proportional to r, but Euclidean space-time diameter proportional to r in space and r² in time).
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/ckn-1982-proof-architecture.md:515:**On Ladyzhenskaya-Seregin (1999):** They simplify the pressure decomposition step (avoiding the harmonic splitting p = p₁ + p₂ by working in a different functional framework), but the ε-regularity criterion and covering argument are identical to CKN.
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/ckn-1982-proof-architecture.md:517:**On Robinson-Rodrigo-Sadowski (2016):** Their Chapter 13 presents the CKN proof in full, including the explicit form of the local energy inequality and the parabolic Sobolev embedding. Their §13.3 has the most explicit treatment of the pressure decomposition.
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/ckn-1982-proof-architecture.md:519:**On ε₀ computability:** As noted in the Atlas NS library (atlas/execution/agents/library/factual/navier-stokes, entry R4 in exploration-001), ε₀ has never been explicitly computed. Lin (1998)'s proof is non-constructive (compactness), so it does not improve this. Vasseur (2007)'s De Giorgi approach also does not yield an explicit ε₀.
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/ckn-1982-proof-architecture.md:521:**Verification note:** The precise form of (LEI-φ) — specifically the coefficient 2 in front of |∇u|² — appears in CKN (2.1). Some textbooks write the NS local energy inequality without the factor of 2 and with a different normalization of viscosity ν. With ν = 1 (CKN normalization), the factor is 2 (from 2ν = 2·1). Care is needed when comparing with papers that use ν explicitly.
