../../../../missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/RESULTS.md:5:All three independent proof strategies (CKN 1982, Lin 1998, Vasseur 2007) reduce to the **same covering argument with the same scaling exponents**. The dimension ≤ 1 bound on the singular set is fundamental to epsilon-regularity approaches, not a proof-specific artifact. Improvement requires a genuinely different proof architecture.
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/RESULTS.md:11:| Feature | CKN (1982) | Lin (1998) | Vasseur (2007) |
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/RESULTS.md:14:| **Pressure requirement** | p in L^{3/2}(Q_r) at every scale | p in L^{3/2}(Q_r) (same as CKN) | P in L^p(L^1), any p > 1 (weaker) |
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/RESULTS.md:15:| **Localization mechanism** | Explicit cutoff functions phi, |nabla phi| ~ 1/r | Blow-up / compactness / contradiction | De Giorgi level-set iteration on shrinking domains Q_k -> Q_inf |
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/RESULTS.md:16:| **Covering argument** | Vitali in parabolic metric, Sum r_i <= (1/eps)int|nabla u|^2 | **Identical to CKN** | **Identical to CKN** |
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/RESULTS.md:21:| **Velocity nonlinear exponent** | 3/2 (from Sobolev L^3 -> L^{3/2} scaling) | Same (hidden) | 5/3 (De Giorgi beats NS scaling) |
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/RESULTS.md:53:### CKN (1982): The reference framework
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/RESULTS.md:59:### Lin (1998): Streamlined but opaque
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/RESULTS.md:62:- **Key insight:** C(r) alone gives only dim <= 2; the dim <= 1 bound specifically requires E(r) from the dissipation integral, reintroduced at the covering step via the local energy inequality
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/RESULTS.md:65:### Vasseur (2007): Sharpest obstruction identification
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/RESULTS.md:66:- De Giorgi iteration achieves **better** velocity exponent: 5/3 > CKN's 3/2
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/RESULTS.md:68:- **Critical finding:** Vasseur's Appendix (Conjecture 14) proves that beta > 3/2 would imply **full regularity** (all suitable weak solutions globally bounded). Current best: beta = 4/3 from local pressure
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/RESULTS.md:69:- The threshold beta = 3/2 precisely separates partial from full regularity in the De Giorgi framework
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/RESULTS.md:70:- Converts "can we prove full regularity?" into "can we control the local pressure term with exponent > 3/2?" — a sharper formulation than CKN provides
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/RESULTS.md:89:- If E(r) stays bounded (saturates at ~ epsilon_0), the CKN bound is essentially tight and no improvement is possible within epsilon-regularity
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/RESULTS.md:93:1. **Tran-Yu (2014, AIHP):** Claims to use De Giorgi + Galilean invariance to remove the "bad scaling" local pressure term. If their approach achieves beta > 3/2, this would be a genuine structural advance. Worth verifying.
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/RESULTS.md:95:3. **Vasseur's Conjecture 14:** The explicit "beta > 3/2 implies full regularity" statement provides a precise target. Any method achieving beta > 3/2 for the local pressure term would resolve the Navier-Stokes regularity problem.
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/RESULTS.md:104:- **Unexpected discovery:** Vasseur's framework identifies the **precise obstruction** to full regularity: the local pressure term with De Giorgi exponent 4/3 < 3/2. The threshold beta = 3/2 separates partial from full regularity. This is more informative than CKN's framework, which does not explicitly identify the full-regularity barrier.
../../planning-runs/run-003/attacks/chain-01.md:9:Its main weakness is that it quietly assumes any genuinely live beyond-De-Giorgi mechanism should appear as an immediate gain on one inherited localized bottleneck after an exact algebraic rewrite of the same quadratic nonlinearity. That is a very strong assumption, and it biases the chain toward proving that reformulations collapse back to the same obstruction. That outcome may be true, but the chain is structurally tilted toward it before the work begins.
../../planning-runs/run-003/attacks/chain-01.md:13:### 1. The chain is framed as "beyond De Giorgi" but still judges progress in De Giorgi-adjacent currency
../../planning-runs/run-003/attacks/chain-01.md:19:### 2. It assumes exact reformulation is a serious source of new leverage rather than mostly a change of presentation
../../planning-runs/run-003/attacks/chain-01.md:21:For exact rewrites of NS, there is a default expectation: once one restores localization, projection, and commutator bookkeeping, the same quadratic structure reappears. The chain knows this, but still treats reformulation as a live discovery direction instead of treating "collapse back to the same estimate" as the generic baseline that must be defeated by a sharply identified mechanism.
../../planning-runs/run-003/attacks/chain-01.md:23:That matters because otherwise Step 2 is not a real test of a broad hypothesis. It is mostly a check of whether a small familiar family of rewrites fails in the familiar way.
../../planning-runs/run-003/attacks/chain-01.md:31:Step 3 is built to strip away gains that are "really" geometric or pressure-tensor effects. That is good if the goal is a pure reformulation result. It is bad if the only real NS-specific cancellations are hybrid: exact algebraic form plus alignment, or rewrite plus concentrated tube geometry, or rewrite plus tensor structure. The chain risks discarding the only live mechanisms because they are not pure enough.
../../planning-runs/run-003/attacks/chain-01.md:35:To promote a positive route, the chain demands a localized gain, Tao relevance, robustness away from special regimes, and a changed closure mechanism. To reach a negative endpoint, it only needs a small shortlist of natural rewrites to collapse back to familiar structure.
../../planning-runs/run-003/attacks/chain-01.md:37:That asymmetry is acceptable if the chain is honestly labeled "cleanup of the exact-rewrite loophole." It is not acceptable if the chain is sold as a serious search for the live beyond-De-Giorgi property.
../../planning-runs/run-003/attacks/chain-01.md:51:- It never says which bottleneck is mission-central. Is it the De Giorgi truncated pressure contribution, a local-energy flux term, a vorticity stretching localization, or some projected interaction? Those are not interchangeable. A rewrite that helps one may do nothing for the others.
../../planning-runs/run-003/attacks/chain-01.md:53:- The shortlist cap of at most three reformulations is efficient but arbitrary. If the screening criteria are vague, the cap mostly encodes prior taste, not mathematical evidence.
../../planning-runs/run-003/attacks/chain-01.md:58:### Step 2 - Test the shortlisted reformulations at the estimate level
../../planning-runs/run-003/attacks/chain-01.md:64:- The natural test family is too familiar. Lamb-vector, projected form, and vorticity transport are exactly the rewrites one would expect to collapse back to the same structure unless some additional mechanism is injected. The mission context already suggests that at least part of this family has been effectively stress-tested.
../../planning-runs/run-003/attacks/chain-01.md:66:- The kill condition is close to tautological. Exact rewrites of the same quadratic nonlinearity generally do return the same Calderon-Zygmund or quadratic estimate once all costs are paid. If the chain only permits exact rewrites and treats that collapse as grounds for termination, then a negative result is the default, not a discovery.
../../planning-runs/run-003/attacks/chain-01.md:67:- The estimate table could flatten important distinctions. Two rewrites may share the same headline scaling but differ in where commutator costs, projector losses, or localization errors appear. If those are not itemized explicitly, the table will overstate sameness.
../../planning-runs/run-003/attacks/chain-01.md:81:- The handoff logic is too clean. If a rewrite only helps when combined with local geometry, that may be evidence of the correct mechanism, not evidence that the reformulation chain failed.
../../planning-runs/run-003/attacks/chain-01.md:93:- The chain assumes that the main valuable positive output would be a closure criterion or theorem target. A sharp obstruction, rigidity statement, or clean no-go theorem for a reformulation family could be more realistic and more valuable.
../../planning-runs/run-003/attacks/chain-01.md:104:- If only a short list of familiar rewrites was tested, the negative claim must be very narrow. It cannot honestly become "exact reformulations do not help" without defining the family much more tightly.
../../planning-runs/run-003/attacks/chain-01.md:106:- The negative endpoint risks conflating "these few natural rewrites collapse" with "reformulation as a strategy is dead." The chain can support the former far more easily than the latter.
../../planning-runs/run-003/attacks/chain-01.md:115:- it can close a specific loophole in the "maybe an exact rewrite creates an SQG-style gain" story;
../../planning-runs/run-003/attacks/chain-01.md:116:- it can produce a bounded negative result on a tightly defined family of exact reformulations;
../../planning-runs/run-003/attacks/chain-01.md:122:2. that algebraic reformulation can be cleanly separated from geometry, tensor structure, or dynamics early enough that those can be treated mainly as contamination.
../../planning-runs/run-003/attacks/chain-01.md:126:This is a good chain for proving that a small family of exact Navier-Stokes rewrites does not magically create an SQG-like gain inside the current local estimate architecture. It is a weak chain for discovering new structure, because it searches in a narrow place and judges success in the language of the architecture that has already failed.
