../../../../missions/vasseur-pressure/MISSION-COMPLETE.md:1:# Mission Complete: Vasseur Pressure Threshold
../../../../missions/vasseur-pressure/MISSION-COMPLETE.md:3:**Mission:** Determine whether the Vasseur pressure exponent gap (β = 4/3, need β > 3/2) can be closed using H^1 structure of the pressure from compensated compactness.
../../../../missions/vasseur-pressure/MISSION-COMPLETE.md:5:**Result:** Negative. The H^1 route is a structural dead end for De Giorgi iteration on Navier-Stokes. The obstruction is fundamental, not a proof artifact.
../../../../missions/vasseur-pressure/MISSION-COMPLETE.md:15:Vasseur (2007) showed that full Navier-Stokes regularity follows if the local pressure exponent β exceeds 3/2. Current best: β = 4/3. The gap is 1/6. Can compensated compactness (which places the pressure in Hardy space H^1 for divergence-free velocity fields) close this gap?
../../../../missions/vasseur-pressure/MISSION-COMPLETE.md:23:**Idea:** If De Giorgi test functions ψ_k are BMO-bounded, then H^1-BMO duality replaces the Hölder estimate for the pressure pairing, potentially making the far-field pressure coefficient U_k-dependent.
../../../../missions/vasseur-pressure/MISSION-COMPLETE.md:26:1. W^{1,2}(ℝ^3) does not embed into BMO(ℝ^3). You need W^{1,3}. De Giorgi energy U_k only controls W^{1,2}. So ||ψ_k||_{BMO} cannot be bounded from U_k.
../../../../missions/vasseur-pressure/MISSION-COMPLETE.md:28:3. Localizing to Q_k (which De Giorgi requires) destroys H^1 structure: cutoffs break the mean-zero atom property.
../../../../missions/vasseur-pressure/MISSION-COMPLETE.md:36:**Why it fails:** The cancellation gain and the gradient cost exactly cancel at the optimal scale ρ ~ 2^{-2k}. Sharp, not loose. Additionally, De Giorgi test functions ψ_k ≥ 0 (non-negative truncation), which wastes all atomic cancellation — atoms need oscillating test functions.
../../../../missions/vasseur-pressure/MISSION-COMPLETE.md:54:| p_θ > 4/3 in interpolation | De Giorgi recursion needs it | p_θ < 4/3 from H^1 ⊂ L^1 |
../../../../missions/vasseur-pressure/MISSION-COMPLETE.md:58:**Conclusion:** The Vasseur pressure gap cannot be closed by any method that (a) works within the Leray-Hopf energy class and (b) uses H^1 structure of pressure. The gap requires either a regularity gain beyond W^{1,2}, an approach that doesn't pair pressure against De Giorgi test functions, or abandoning the De Giorgi framework.
../../../../missions/vasseur-pressure/MISSION-COMPLETE.md:64:- β = 4/3 confirmed as current best, unchanged since Vasseur 2007 (19 years)
../../../../missions/vasseur-pressure/MISSION-COMPLETE.md:65:- β > 3/2 confirmed as the full regularity threshold (Vasseur's Conjecture 14)
../../../../missions/vasseur-pressure/MISSION-COMPLETE.md:66:- "Tran-Yu 2014 AIHP" does not exist — hallucinated citation. Real paper: Choi-Vasseur 2014 (arXiv:1105.1526)
../../../../missions/vasseur-pressure/MISSION-COMPLETE.md:67:- H^1 + De Giorgi is well-studied by the Vasseur school, BUT H^1-BMO duality specifically was untried
../../../../missions/vasseur-pressure/MISSION-COMPLETE.md:68:- Vasseur school moved to vorticity methods in 2021, implicitly declaring H^1 pressure ceiling reached
../../../../missions/vasseur-pressure/MISSION-COMPLETE.md:77:A complete obstruction map explaining WHY H^1 pressure structure cannot improve De Giorgi regularity for NS, with three independent proofs and a unifying structural explanation (the W^{1,3} wall).
../../../../missions/vasseur-pressure/MISSION-COMPLETE.md:80:1. The Vasseur school's pivot to vorticity (2021) is structurally justified — the H^1 pressure route is a genuine dead end.
../../../../missions/vasseur-pressure/MISSION-COMPLETE.md:88:2. **Lorentz-space De Giorgi.** The L^{3/2,∞} weak-type estimate is available but unexploited. A De Giorgi framework using weak-type norms directly could sidestep the strong-type CZ ceiling.
../../../../missions/vasseur-pressure/MISSION-COMPLETE.md:89:3. **Fractional regularity.** The step between W^{1,2} and W^{1,3} is fractional. Fractional De Giorgi methods might provide W^{s,2} with s > 1 — BMO embedding requires s·2 = 3, i.e., s = 3/2.
../../../../missions/vasseur-pressure/MISSION-COMPLETE.md:100:2. **Element transfer worked.** The Final Decider merged Chain 1's orientation step and Chain 4's Caffarelli-Vasseur comparison into the Chain 2 winner. Both proved essential.
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/lin-1998-proof-architecture.md:1:# Exploration 002: Lin (1998) Proof Architecture — REPORT
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/lin-1998-proof-architecture.md:3:**Goal:** Analyze Fanghua Lin's simplified proof (1998) of the CKN partial regularity theorem. Extract 5 structural features and compare with CKN (1982).
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/lin-1998-proof-architecture.md:5:**Paper:** Fanghua Lin, "A new proof of the Caffarelli-Kohn-Nirenberg theorem," *Communications on Pure and Applied Mathematics*, 51(3):241-257, 1998.
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/lin-1998-proof-architecture.md:7:**Also consulted:** Ladyzhenskaya and Seregin, "On partial regularity of suitable weak solutions to the three-dimensional Navier-Stokes equations," *J. Math. Fluid Mech.* 1 (1999), 356–387. (A parallel simplification appearing the same year, largely confirming Lin's approach.)
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/lin-1998-proof-architecture.md:17:Lin works in exactly the same setting as CKN: suitable weak solutions (u, p) of 3D incompressible NS on a space-time domain Q ⊆ ℝ³ × ℝ, with the local energy inequality (LEI). The parabolic cylinders Q_r(z₀) = B_r(x₀) × (t₀ − r², t₀) and scale-invariant quantities are identical to CKN.
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/lin-1998-proof-architecture.md:19:Lin's claimed contribution is a shorter proof of the same theorem: P¹(Σ) = 0, where Σ is the parabolic singular set and P¹ is parabolic 1-dimensional Hausdorff measure.
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/lin-1998-proof-architecture.md:21:**The key structural choice:** Lin replaces CKN's direct quantitative energy estimates (explicit cutoff-function PDE estimates) with a **contradiction + compactness** argument. The proof is by contradiction: assuming a sequence of "almost-singular" points exists, Lin derives a contradiction by passing to a limit and using properties of the limiting solution.
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/lin-1998-proof-architecture.md:27:### Lin's Criterion (Lin 1998, Theorem 1.1)
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/lin-1998-proof-architecture.md:29:Lin uses the following ε-regularity criterion (his Theorem 1.1, which he states and proves first):
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/lin-1998-proof-architecture.md:31:**Lin's Epsilon-Regularity:** There exists an absolute constant ε₀ > 0 such that if (u, p) is a suitable weak solution on Q_1(0,0) with f ∈ L^q (q > 5/2), and:
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/lin-1998-proof-architecture.md:37:In the scale-invariant notation of CKN, this reads:
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/lin-1998-proof-architecture.md:41:**Critical comparison with CKN (1982):**

