../../../../missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-001/attacks/chain-02.md:1:# Attack on Chain 02 - SQG-Type Cancellation via Lamb Vector Reformulation
../../../../missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-001/attacks/chain-02.md:5:This chain is attacking the right high-upside question, but it is structurally at risk of confusing an algebraic rewrite with a usable estimate. The central analogy to SQG is weaker than the chain admits: in SQG, the first-order commutator is tied to scalar transport and a linear constitutive law, while in NS the Lamb-vector / vorticity / Helmholtz forms are mostly equivalent repackagings of the same quadratic vector interaction. Unless the chain screens candidates at the level of the actual localized or truncated estimate that matters, it can spend several steps rediscovering textbook identities and then either overclaim a negative result or drift into Chain 03's Beltrami geometry.
../../../../missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-001/attacks/chain-02.md:13:- The hidden assumption is that a side-by-side comparison across velocity, vorticity, Lamb-vector, and Helmholtz-projected forms can reveal a genuinely new "slot" for SQG-style cancellation. That is not obvious. These are equivalent formulations before truncation/localization, and the mission-context obstruction is precisely that the bad behavior appears after truncation/localization.
../../../../missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-001/attacks/chain-02.md:20:### Step 2 - Test candidate reformulations algebraically
../../../../missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-001/attacks/chain-02.md:24:- The example identity `u . grad u = grad(|u|^2 / 2) - u x omega` is textbook. After projection, the gradient is removed and one is left with the Lamb-vector term. That does not by itself reduce derivative count or remove quadraticity; it just relocates them.
../../../../missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-001/attacks/chain-02.md:30:Concrete failure mode: Step 2 may conclude that a projected Lamb-vector form is "best" because it isolates the nonlinearity cleanly, but that is largely cosmetic unless the chain shows an actual improvement on the bad localized term rather than a cleaner decomposition.
../../../../missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-001/attacks/chain-02.md:36:- Testing exact Beltrami flows is a weak stress test for an allegedly generic NS mechanism. Exact Beltrami is a highly nongeneric symmetry class where the Lamb vector vanishes by design. Success there proves almost nothing.
../../../../missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-001/attacks/chain-02.md:40:- This step overlaps heavily with Chain 03. Once the test object becomes "Beltrami alignment plus perturbations," the chain has drifted from algebraic reformulation into geometry-first fragility analysis. That weakens the claim that Chain 02 is meaningfully distinct.
../../../../missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-001/attacks/chain-02.md:51:- The step also inherits the contamination from Step 3. If the surviving mechanism is really a near-Beltrami geometry effect, then the chain should close by handing that result to the geometry branch, not by presenting it as an algebraic reformulation win.
../../../../missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-001/attacks/chain-02.md:68:- Beltrami/Lamb-vector fragility is also already on record.
../../../../missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-001/attacks/chain-02.md:91:- It has a legitimate negative payload if tightened: a careful memo saying that the standard Lamb-vector / projected / vorticity rewrites do not improve the operative localized estimate would be genuinely useful.
../../../../missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-001/attacks/chain-02.md:95:- As written, the chain is too likely to mistake reformulation for mechanism.
../../../../missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-001/mission-context.md:19:- The Lamb vector L = ω × u generates the CZ-lossy pressure piece. For Beltrami flows (L = 0), CZ loss vanishes — but mechanism doesn't survive even 1% perturbation from Beltrami alignment.
