../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/vasseur-2007-proof-architecture.md:133:- For p ≤ 10: β_p ∈ (1, 4/3) (the "bad" local pressure term limits β)
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/vasseur-2007-proof-architecture.md:168:- **P_k^2 is local:** −ΔP_k^2 = ∂_i∂_j[φ_k u_i u_j] on R³. This depends only on u inside B_{k−1}. The local pressure is further decomposed into three pieces P_k^{21}, P_k^{22}, P_k^{23} based on splitting u = u·(1 − v_k/|u|) + u·v_k/|u|, where the first factor is bounded by 1 (since |u|·(1−v_k/|u|) ≤ C_k ≤ 1) and the second depends on the level-set energy.
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/vasseur-2007-proof-architecture.md:172:### The Obstruction: Local Pressure Term P_k^{21}
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/vasseur-2007-proof-architecture.md:174:The P_k^{21} piece (harmonic component estimated via the bounded part of u) produces the estimate (Step 5, eq. (20)):
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/vasseur-2007-proof-architecture.md:176:  |P_k^{21} terms| ≤ C_q·2^{kα_q}·U_{k-1}^{4/3 − 5/(3q)}
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/vasseur-2007-proof-architecture.md:178:The minimum over q of 4/3 − 5/(3q) as q → ∞ approaches **4/3**. This is the fundamental obstruction:
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/vasseur-2007-proof-architecture.md:179:- The exponent 4/3 > 1, so β_p > 1 still holds: partial regularity follows.
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/vasseur-2007-proof-architecture.md:180:- But 4/3 < 3/2, so Vaseur **cannot** achieve β_p > 3/2 for all p.
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/vasseur-2007-proof-architecture.md:182:Vasseur writes explicitly: "the only bad terms (with exponent smaller than 3/2) comes from the local pressure term which cannot be written in a divergence form."
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/vasseur-2007-proof-architecture.md:191:| Main lossiness source | Cutoff ∇η terms + pressure L^{3/2} → 3/2 scaling | Same (but obscured by contradiction) | P_k^{21} local pressure → exponent 4/3 |
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/vasseur-2007-proof-architecture.md:192:| Does it change the bottleneck? | No | No | No (still 4/3 < 3/2; only partial regularity) |
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/vasseur-2007-proof-architecture.md:243:| Local pressure P_k^{21} (bounded-|u| part) | β → 4/3 (as q → ∞) | Calderón-Zygmund on bounded×v_k terms |
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/vasseur-2007-proof-architecture.md:244:| Non-local pressure P_k^1 (harmonic part) | β > 1 (any p > 1) | Mean value inequality for harmonic functions |
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/vasseur-2007-proof-architecture.md:246:**Minimum exponent = 4/3 > 1.** Partial regularity follows (β_p > 1 for all p > 1).
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/vasseur-2007-proof-architecture.md:257:Vasseur's transport terms give **5/3 > 3/2** (better than CKN), but the local pressure term gives **4/3 < 3/2** (worse, in the sense of being farther from full regularity). So:
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/vasseur-2007-proof-architecture.md:259:- **Where De Giorgi hits a new wall:** local pressure (4/3 — a new obstruction not visible in CKN)
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/vasseur-2007-proof-architecture.md:264:Vasseur shows (Appendix, Conjecture 14): **if** Proposition 3 held with β_p > 3/2, then ALL suitable weak solutions would be globally bounded (full regularity). The proof rescales u_ε(t,x) = ελu(t₀+λ²t, x₀+λx); the rescaled initial energy U_{ε,0} ~ ε^{2−5/λ}·(global energy)·λ → 0 as λ → 0 when 2β − 3 > 0 ↔ β > 3/2. So the threshold β = 3/2 is **precisely the boundary between partial and full regularity** in the De Giorgi framework. The current proof achieves β = 4/3 (limited by local pressure), which falls short.
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/vasseur-2007-proof-architecture.md:276:2. **The exponent 4/3 from P_k^{21}** (see above). This is a fundamental loss — the pressure cannot be written in divergence form, so the Riesz transform estimate loses a factor. No ε-absorption can recover this. It is a **hard structural bound**, not a proof-technique artifact.
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/vasseur-2007-proof-architecture.md:288:**Vasseur avoids this ε-absorption entirely** for the level-set energy estimates, replacing it with the De Giorgi mechanism (Lemma 12 + superlinear recursion). However, the pressure localization still requires Calderón-Zygmund estimates with **fixed L^q constants** (not optimal, but existential), which is where the 4/3 exponent arises.
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/vasseur-2007-proof-architecture.md:304:| Pressure local term | 3/2 (L^{3/2} pressure directly) | 4/3 (harmonic/CZ; *looser* than CKN for this term) |
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/vasseur-2007-proof-architecture.md:309:**Conclusion:** De Giorgi produces tighter estimates for the velocity/transport terms (5/3 vs 3/2), but the pressure localization in Vasseur's approach produces a new obstruction at exponent 4/3. The proof is less lossy on the nonlinear terms but encounters a new pressure bottleneck. Both proofs reach the same conclusion (partial regularity, H¹(S) = 0) but via different "weakest links."
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/vasseur-2007-proof-architecture.md:333:4. **Full regularity is not achieved:** Both proofs face an exponent barrier. In CKN, it is the natural NS scaling (3/2 exponent for the nonlinear term). In Vasseur, the barrier is at exponent 4/3 from the local pressure term — actually a *harder* obstruction (lower exponent), though still > 1.
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/vasseur-2007-proof-architecture.md:339:**What Vasseur's proof does offer** is a structural identification of the obstruction to full regularity: the local pressure term P_k^{21} gives exponent 4/3, and Vasseur proves (Appendix) that β > 3/2 would imply full regularity. So Vasseur's framework converts the question "can we prove full regularity?" into "can we control the local pressure term with exponent > 3/2?" — a more precise formulation than CKN provides.
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/vasseur-2007-proof-architecture.md:345:1. **Exact form of P_k^{22}, P_k^{23} decomposition:** The three-way split of the local pressure is described in general terms by Vasseur; extracting the exact exponents (5/3 for P_k^{22,23}) requires working through Lemmas 9-10 in detail, which are only summarized here.
../../../../missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/vasseur-2007-proof-architecture.md:349:3. **Whether any subsequent work has improved the exponent 4/3 for the local pressure:** A search of post-2007 literature found Caffarelli-Vasseur (2010, SQG equation, different PDE) and Tran-Yu (2014, Galilean invariance argument) but did not fully verify whether Tran-Yu's approach achieves β > 3/2 for NS itself.
../../../../missions/vasseur-pressure/library-inbox/exploration-002-interpolation-route-failure.md:1:# Exploration 002: Interpolation Route — (H^1, L^{4/3})_{θ,q}
../../../../missions/vasseur-pressure/library-inbox/exploration-002-interpolation-route-failure.md:5:Determine whether the interpolation spaces (H^1, L^{4/3})_{θ,q} provide any function space structure exploitable by the De Giorgi energy iteration, with the aim of improving the pressure exponent from β = 4/3 toward β > 3/2.
../../../../missions/vasseur-pressure/library-inbox/exploration-002-interpolation-route-failure.md:13:We have p ∈ H^1(ℝ^3) (CLMS 1993) and p ∈ L^{4/3}(Q_k) (CZ applied to u ∈ L^{8/3}_t L^4_x). The question is whether the intersection structure (H^1, L^{4/3})_{θ,q} provides strictly more than L^{4/3} alone.
../../../../missions/vasseur-pressure/library-inbox/exploration-002-interpolation-route-failure.md:15:### 1.2 Complex Interpolation [H^1, L^{4/3}]_θ
../../../../missions/vasseur-pressure/library-inbox/exploration-002-interpolation-route-failure.md:21:For p = 4/3: 1/p_θ = 1 - θ/4, so p_θ = 4/(4-θ).
../../../../missions/vasseur-pressure/library-inbox/exploration-002-interpolation-route-failure.md:35:| 1.0 | 1.333 = 4/3    | [COMPUTED] |
../../../../missions/vasseur-pressure/library-inbox/exploration-002-interpolation-route-failure.md:37:**Key observation:** For all θ ∈ (0,1), p_θ ∈ (1, 4/3). The complex interpolation gives strictly WORSE Lebesgue integrability than L^{4/3}. Since p_θ < 4/3 < ∞, on a bounded domain Q_k:
../../../../missions/vasseur-pressure/library-inbox/exploration-002-interpolation-route-failure.md:39:   L^{4/3}(Q_k) ⊂ L^{p_θ}(Q_k)  (p_θ < 4/3)
../../../../missions/vasseur-pressure/library-inbox/exploration-002-interpolation-route-failure.md:41:So p ∈ L^{4/3}(Q_k) already implies p ∈ [H^1, L^{4/3}]_θ(Q_k). The complex interpolation space is a LARGER class, providing weaker information. [COMPUTED]
../../../../missions/vasseur-pressure/library-inbox/exploration-002-interpolation-route-failure.md:45:**Verification (Calderón's theorem for H^p):** The result [H^{p_0}, H^{p_1}]_θ = H^p with 1/p = (1-θ)/p_0 + θ/p_1 is classical (Calderón 1964 for the disc; Fefferman-Stein 1972 for ℝ^n via Riesz transforms). For p_1 = 4/3 > 1: H^{4/3} = L^{4/3} because the Riesz transforms are bounded on L^{4/3}. The interpolation gives H^{p_θ} = L^{p_θ} since p_θ > 1. [CHECKED against Fefferman-Stein 1972 and Stein "Harmonic Analysis" Chapter III]
../../../../missions/vasseur-pressure/library-inbox/exploration-002-interpolation-route-failure.md:47:### 1.3 Real Interpolation (H^1, L^{4/3})_{θ,q}
../../../../missions/vasseur-pressure/library-inbox/exploration-002-interpolation-route-failure.md:50:   K(t, f; H^1, L^{4/3}) = inf_{f = f_0 + f_1} (||f_0||_{H^1} + t||f_1||_{L^{4/3}})
../../../../missions/vasseur-pressure/library-inbox/exploration-002-interpolation-route-failure.md:53:   K(t, f; H^1, L^{4/3}) ≥ K(t, f; L^1, L^{4/3})
../../../../missions/vasseur-pressure/library-inbox/exploration-002-interpolation-route-failure.md:55:The real interpolation norm ||f||_{(H^1, L^{4/3})_{θ,q}} ≥ ||f||_{(L^1, L^{4/3})_{θ,q}} = ||f||_{L^{p_θ, q}}
../../../../missions/vasseur-pressure/library-inbox/exploration-002-interpolation-route-failure.md:59:**The direction of inclusion:** Because H^1 ↪ L^1 with ||·||_{H^1} ≥ ||·||_{L^1}, the infimum in the K-functional for (H^1, L^{4/3}) is taken over a *smaller set of decompositions* f = f_0 + f_1 where f_0 ∈ H^1 (more restrictive than f_0 ∈ L^1). Therefore:
../../../../missions/vasseur-pressure/library-inbox/exploration-002-interpolation-route-failure.md:61:   (H^1, L^{4/3})_{θ,q} ⊂ L^{p_θ, q} = (L^1, L^{4/3})_{θ,q}
../../../../missions/vasseur-pressure/library-inbox/exploration-002-interpolation-route-failure.md:63:The interpolation space is a SUBSPACE of the Lorentz space — it is MORE restrictive in membership, but does not provide better ESTIMATES for functions that are already in L^{4/3}. [COMPUTED — see code/k_functional_analysis.py]
../../../../missions/vasseur-pressure/library-inbox/exploration-002-interpolation-route-failure.md:65:**The cancellation question:** Does the real interpolation space (H^1, L^{4/3})_{θ,q} carry cancellation conditions beyond the Lorentz space?
